A favoritism capitalism à the American style
Do you remember the East Asia crisis? When the U.S. Treasury department and its IMF allies blamed the problems of this region on a favoritism capitalism, lack of transparency, and an inefficient government?
The countries were encouraged to follow the American model, to use American accounting audit firms, to introduce American entrepreneurs to teach them how to manage their businesses.
Regardless of whether under the authority of its own entrepreneurs, East Asia developed faster than any other region - and with greater stability - over the last three decades.
The growing Enron scandal gives a new meaning to two well-known American proverbs: "We reap what we sow" and "It takes no faults to criticize others".
Enron used large accounting schemes and complex financial products (derivatives) to mislead investors about its value.
No transparency here.
It used its money to acquire influence and power, shape US energy policy, and avoid regulations.
Croney capitalism is not new, nor is it exclusive to a single party.
The former US Secretary of the Treasury, Robert Rubin, would have attempted to influence the current government to intervene on behalf of Enron in the disputed conflict in India.
When he was in office, he intervened when the supposedly independent accounting standards board tried to clean up corporate accounts with a generous handout to top executives.
It was partly due to him that this effort to make corporate accounting more transparent was thwarted.
The enthusiasm of America to bail out airlines with several billion dollars or to create cartels to protect its steel and aluminum industries suggests that the ideology of free market is just a thin veil for the well-being of old businesses: giving to those who have the right connections.
For some, the fact that Enron was not bailed out and the problems were not revealed is a sign of the absence of crony capitalism.
My interpretation is different: it is a sign of the importance of a free press that can stop abuses but can also reduce them.
When the press started looking into Enron, the number of Congress members who had accepted Enron money was revealed.
Campaign contributions were not just about public interest, but rather an investment.
Like most Enron investments, everything went well in the short term, but failed to produce results in the long term.
Several lessons can be learned from this company.
Some of these concern politics: the Enron scandal strengthens arguments in favor of reforming campaign financing and the need for even more effective laws that will be made public.
Democracies are undermined by business interests that can in fact buy elections.
The Bush administration, however, refuses to disclose information that would confirm the role of business interests in defining its energy policy.
Other lessons are drawn from the economy, particularly from the information economy.
For markets to function, for the appropriate signals to be provided to allocate resources efficiently, investors must receive as much information as possible.
There are inherent conflicts of interest: owners and managers are naturally motivated to present as rosy a picture as possible.
The accounting control is intended to set limits on potential abuses.
But who will keep the keepers?
Who will control the account controllers?
We are counting a lot on the motivations.
The auditors want to maintain their reputation.
But the relationship between auditing and accounting practices brings forth other perverted motivations: a motivation to please clients who do not appreciate unfavorable reports.
Arthur Levitt, the former chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission, acknowledged the conflict: given that many within accounting firms focus on their own short-term interests, the integrity of audits might be compromised.
He is probably the unsung hero of the debacle.
But accounting firms and their corporate clients - hardly surprising, given the cabal that developed - fiercely attacked his proposal to separate auditing and accounting activities.
What Levitt understood - and what the Enron debacle so clearly showed - is that motivations are important, but that unregulated markets cannot provide the best motivations on their own.
The markets cannot provide motivations for the creation of wealth; they can provide motivations for the type of combinations that Enron implemented.
The new economy - and its new complex financial instruments - highlight the problems of reliable accounting control structures; they make it easier to confuse them.
Instead of facing the problems, American business systematically turns its back on them, supported and encouraged by American crony capitalism.
The major problem of our era is to find a balance between government and market.
The status quo will claim that Enron is an exception: that its disappearance was due to fraud, that we have laws against fraud and that those who violate these laws must face the consequences and will face them.
But the majority of Enron's actions were legal.
Its auditors declare that its central practices obeyed the law and that thousands of companies act the same way.
They are right - and that is precisely the problem.
Investors need to be sure that the information received reflects sufficiently the economic situation of a company.
In the current regulatory and legal framework, with derivatives and other off-balance-sheet liabilities, investors have no possibility of being given those guarantees at present.
We need better standards and more effective laws.
Although we'll never be able to prevent all abuses, we can check the motivations.
We can try to inculcate better ethical standards.
But we can't rely on them when so many people in the world don't see anything wrong with the "revolving door" phenomenon.
They claim to manage conflicts of interest, but we find out that they can manage them in their own interests.
But even when evidence of this type of abuse becomes obvious, new places of abuse are created many times - take the American repeal of the Glass Steagall Act, which separated commercial from investments.
We have repeatedly observed the consequences of the excesses of unbridled market freedom.
We must now resist the temptation to tip towards the other extreme.
The challenge to be met is to achieve a just balance.
